# LifeOS Product & UI Rules

## Product Identity

LifeOS is not just a productivity app.

It is a personal life management platform designed to help users:
- organize daily life
- build consistency
- reflect on habits and moods
- improve productivity
- gain useful personal insights

The product should feel:
- calm
- modern
- thoughtful
- motivating
- structured
- human

## Product Vision

Core mission:
> Help users become more consistent, mindful, and productive through structured daily tracking and meaningful insights.

Every feature and UI decision must support this mission.

Do not add features that feel random, noisy, or disconnected from the LifeOS purpose.

## Core Experience Principles

LifeOS should feel like:
- a trusted personal system
- a focused daily companion
- a clean and premium mobile product
- something users want to open every day

The app must not feel:
- stressful
- cluttered
- childish
- overly gamified
- visually noisy
- enterprise-heavy

## UI Philosophy

All UI must be:
- clean
- spacious
- calm
- clear
- modern
- mobile-first
- premium but simple

Prefer:
- strong visual hierarchy
- soft cards
- clear sections
- restrained color usage
- consistent spacing
- obvious actions
- readable typography

Avoid:
- over-decoration
- harsh visual density
- too many colors
- excessive borders
- inconsistent spacing
- large blocks of unstructured content

## Design Tone

LifeOS should visually communicate:
- clarity
- balance
- momentum
- self-improvement
- personal care

The interface should feel emotionally supportive, not cold or mechanical.

## Screen Design Rules

Every screen should have:
- one clear purpose
- strong information hierarchy
- obvious primary action
- breathing room
- clean spacing
- clear state handling

Every screen must account for:
- empty state
- loading state
- error state
- success state where relevant

Do not create screens that dump too much information at once.

## Mobile-First Rules

This is primarily a mobile product.

Rules:
- optimize layout for small screens first
- keep interactions thumb-friendly
- avoid cramped layouts
- prioritize quick scanning
- reduce friction for repeated daily actions

Key actions such as logging mood, completing a habit, writing a journal entry, or adding a task must feel fast and effortless.

## Component Rules

Components should be:
- reusable when meaningful
- visually consistent
- minimal
- easy to understand

Preferred reusable components:
- cards
- section headers
- progress widgets
- list items
- chips/tags
- empty states
- loading placeholders
- buttons
- input fields

Do not create too many one-off component styles.

## Typography Rules

Use typography to create hierarchy.

Rules:
- titles should be clear and strong
- section labels should be readable
- secondary text should be subtle but legible
- body text must be easy to read
- avoid too many text sizes in one screen
- avoid weak hierarchy

Text should always feel deliberate and calm.

## Spacing Rules

Spacing must be consistent.

Rules:
- use a predictable spacing system
- give content room to breathe
- separate sections clearly
- avoid crowded cards and lists
- avoid arbitrary spacing choices

Good spacing is part of the premium feel.

## Color Rules

Use restrained color intentionally.

Rules:
- keep palette minimal
- use color to support hierarchy and meaning
- avoid rainbow-style UI
- mood colors can be expressive but still controlled
- status colors should be consistent
- do not let color overwhelm the experience

The overall product should still feel calm.

## Interaction Rules

Interactions should be:
- smooth
- obvious
- low-friction
- supportive

Prefer:
- clear tap targets
- fast flows
- useful confirmations
- predictable gestures
- minimal cognitive load

Avoid:
- overcomplicated multi-step flows
- hidden actions
- confusing gestures
- too many modals for routine tasks

## UX Rules by Domain

### Tasks
Tasks should feel fast and structured.
Users should be able to:
- quickly create tasks
- see priorities clearly
- mark completion easily
- understand what matters today

### Habits
Habits should feel motivating, not stressful.
Users should be able to:
- check in quickly
- understand streaks easily
- see progress over time
- stay encouraged

### Journal
Journaling should feel private and reflective.
Users should be able to:
- write without distraction
- review past entries comfortably
- feel safe and focused

### Mood Tracking
Mood tracking should be simple and lightweight.
Users should be able to:
- log mood in seconds
- review patterns visually
- understand emotional trends clearly

### Insights
Insights should feel meaningful and understandable.
Users should be able to:
- see useful summaries
- notice patterns
- understand progress
- avoid confusing analytics dashboards

## Empty State Rules

Empty states must be helpful, not generic.

Rules:
- explain what the feature is for
- encourage the next action
- keep tone supportive
- avoid lifeless placeholders

Example feeling:
- "Start your first habit"
- "Write your first journal entry"
- "Track today's mood to start building insight"

## Loading State Rules

Loading states should feel polished.

Rules:
- use skeletons or subtle placeholders where appropriate
- avoid abrupt blank screens
- keep perceived performance smooth

## Error State Rules

Error states must be calm and clear.

Rules:
- explain what went wrong simply
- provide retry when appropriate
- do not blame the user
- do not expose technical details

## Content Tone Rules

Microcopy should feel:
- supportive
- clear
- human
- concise

Avoid:
- robotic system language
- overly corporate tone
- aggressive productivity language
- guilt-based messaging

LifeOS should encourage progress, not pressure.

## Product Scope Discipline

Only add features that strengthen the core product.

Good feature categories:
- daily planning
- routine tracking
- reflection
- emotional awareness
- trend visibility
- insight generation

Avoid features that dilute focus unless clearly strategic.

## Portfolio Quality Rule

This project must be good enough to showcase publicly.

That means:
- UI should look intentional and premium
- feature set should feel real
- flows should feel thought through
- screens should look production-ready
- product direction must stay cohesive

## Things Cursor Must Avoid

Do not:
- create visually noisy screens
- add random dashboard clutter
- use too many colors or styles
- create inconsistent components
- make the product feel generic
- over-gamify the experience
- use weak spacing or weak hierarchy
- generate features outside the LifeOS mission
- create UX that feels stressful or confusing

## Definition of Done

A product/UI feature is complete only when:
- it supports the LifeOS mission
- it has a clear user purpose
- the screen has strong hierarchy
- spacing and typography feel polished
- loading/empty/error states exist
- the flow feels smooth on mobile
- the UI looks consistent and premium
- the feature feels useful, not decorative

## Cursor Behavior Rule

When generating product decisions, screens, UX flows, or UI for LifeOS:
- think like a senior product designer + product engineer
- protect the product vision
- prioritize calm clarity
- make the app feel premium, modern, and human
- always choose usability over visual noise
